üåê Azure Virtual Network Analysis Report

Virtual WAN Migration Planning Report

Generated on August 28, 2025 at 09:27

üìã Data Collection Methodology

üîç Data Source & Collection

  • Analysis Date: August 28, 2025
  • Scope: All enabled Azure subscriptions across the entire tenant
  • Region Filter: Australia East region only
  • Discovery Method: Network-first approach using Azure PowerShell Az modules
  • Authentication: Current user's Azure login credentials with cross-subscription access

üï∑Ô∏è Discovery Process

  1. Virtual Network Discovery: Enumerated all VNets in australiaeast region across all subscriptions using Get-AzVirtualNetwork
  2. Subnet Analysis: Analyzed each subnet within discovered VNets for IP configuration assignments
  3. Network Interface Tracing: Traced IP configurations to network interfaces using Get-AzNetworkInterface
  4. VM Discovery: Identified VMs attached to network interfaces, including cross-resource group and cross-subscription VMs
  5. Resource Metadata: Collected VM details, tags, resource groups, and subscription information for each discovered resource

üè∑Ô∏è Workload Classification Logic

Production Classification: Resources containing any of these keywords in VM name, resource group name, or subscription name:

'prod', 'production', 'live', 'prd'

Non-Production Classification: Resources containing any of these keywords:

'dev', 'development', 'test', 'staging', 'uat', 'sit', 'nonprod', 'non-prod', 'sandbox', 'poc', 'demo'

Unknown Classification: Resources that don't match any of the above patterns

‚ö†Ô∏è Important Notes

  • Network-First Approach: This analysis traces from VNet subnets to connected resources, ensuring comprehensive discovery regardless of resource group location
  • Cross-Subscription Discovery: VMs in different subscriptions from their VNets are properly discovered and attributed
  • Classification Accuracy: Workload classifications are based on naming conventions and may require manual review for accuracy
  • Tag Dependencies: VM tags are crucial for application team mapping and should be reviewed for completeness
